king about the need for tests to execute under Native Image by default to catch dynamic class loading errors.  \\n\\nIt seems that skipping for UnsupportedOperation on JVM when the module is not open might not be the best approach. Maybe removing this skip is better since it could lead to silent coverage issues. I'm also pondering the potential failures with JDK25 if the necessary modules aren’t opened.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Optimizing for test coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering the situation with Java 25. If the Unsafe `defineClass` is still unavailable, the failure will show up, but it seems like the workflow might be using JDK 21, which could complicate things. The rules mention that prerequisites assume JDK 21, so I think we should aim for coverage rather than just passing tests that are unsupported.  \\n\\nIf I remove the skip and Java 25 still has issues with UsingUnsafe, it might fail. However, if I keep the skip, the tests would pass but wouldn’t provide any coverage.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_FrH48TEshlxzxD7eCc68CPDA|fc_073d83a1f8dec244016a03ba1936dc81979292f18c0a35219d", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -R \"class NativeImageSupport\" -n . ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1 2>/dev/null | head"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1148, "output": 1911, "cacheRead": 66048, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 69107, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778629115242, "responseId": "resp_073d83a1f8dec244016a03b9fc3e288197ba7e61fa56338b3f"}}
